          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be a (complex) linear algebraic group.</fr:p>
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
      If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> is a maximal torus of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, with Weyl group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex>, then

      <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>400</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.1.6.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.1.6.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.1.6.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           \operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_G,\mathbb {Q})           \xrightarrow {\sim } \operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_T,\mathbb {Q})^W.         \tag{6.1.6.1}         ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
      If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> is a torus with character group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X(T)]]></fr:tex>, then

      <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>401</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.1.6.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.1.6.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.1.6.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           \operatorname {H}^\bullet (T,\mathbb {Z})           \simeq  \bigwedge ^\bullet  X(T)         \tag{6.1.6.2}         ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

      (an isomorphism of graded Hopf algebras).
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>
<fr:p>We will only use (a) in the following weaker form:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a') &quot;">
        <fr:em>(The splitting principle).</fr:em>
        The map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_G,\mathbb {Q})\to \operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_T,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> is injective.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p><fr:p>For completion, we recall a proof of (a').</fr:p><fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is a Borel subgroup of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>, then the bundle <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_G/B]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B_G]]></fr:tex> is a fibre in flag spaces.
    By [2.1 and 2.6.3, <fr:link type="local" href="D1968.xml" addr="D1968" title="Théorème de Lefschetz et critères de dégénérescence de suites spectrales">D1968</fr:link>], which is better explained in [Proposition 3.1, <fr:link type="local" href="G1970.xml" addr="G1970" title="Periods of integrals on algebraic manifolds, III">G1970</fr:link>], or by [<fr:link type="local" href="B1956.xml" addr="B1956" title="Sur les variétés analytiques complexes">B1956</fr:link>], the Leray spectral sequence of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_G/B\to  B_G]]></fr:tex> degenerates to rational cohomology.
    We thus have that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (B_G,\mathbb {Q})\hookrightarrow \operatorname {H}^\bullet (U_G/B,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>.
    We conclude by noting that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_G/B\sim  B_B\sim  B_T]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter>
